Malaysia Stocks: Ahmad Zaki, Malaysian Air, Proton, Telekom

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-02-28T01:56:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-28/malaysia-stocks-ahmad-zaki-malaysian-air-proton-telekom.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 9:30 a.m. in Kuala Lumpur.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI  Index fell 11.85, or 0.8
percent, to 1,477.42, set for its lowest close since Oct. 5. The
gauge has declined 3 percent this month, headed for its biggest
monthly drop since May.        Ahmad Zaki Resources Bhd . (AZR MK), a builder, tumbled 12
percent to 88.5 sen, headed for its steepest drop since March
10, 2008. The company had a loss of 83.1 million ringgit ($27
million) in the fourth quarter compared with a profit a year
earlier, according to a company statement.    Malaysian Airline System Bhd . (MAS MK), the national
carrier, slid 1 percent to 1.90 ringgit after fourth-quarter
profit fell 65 percent from a year earlier to 225.9 million
ringgit because of a smaller gain from oil-price hedging.        Proton Holdings Bhd . (PROH MK), Malaysiaâ€™s state-controlled
carmaker, fell 3.7 percent to 3.94 ringgit, bound for the
biggest decline since Jan. 31. The company had a net loss of
60.1 million ringgit in the third quarter ended Dec. 31 compared
with a profit of 79.7 million ringgit a year earlier.        Telekom Malaysia Bhd . (T MK), a fixed-lined phone operator
and Internet services provider, rose 1.8 percent to 3.92
ringgit, set for its highest close since May 25, 2009. The
company said fourth-quarter net income rose to 400.6 million
ringgit from 170.3 million ringgit a year earlier, according to
a stock filing. The company also plans a capital distribution to
shareholders of about 1.04 billion ringgit, or 29 sen a share,
it said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
